value.value: A white crystalline carbohydrate, typically sucrose, used as a sweetener and preservative.
A follicular lymphoma with diffuse pattern characterized by the presence of 6-15 centroblasts per 40 high-power fields.
A species of land snail in the family Helicidae native to the Mediterranean area and western Europe but widely distributed throughout temperate regions worldwide.
An extract of Agaricus bisporus, also known as cultivated mushroom, button mushroom and common mushroom.

label.value: Primary Cutaneous CD30-Positive T-Cell Lymphoproliferative Disorder

value.value: A spectrum of lymphoproliferative disorders characterized by CD30 (Ki-1)-positive cutaneous T-cell infiltrates. The two ends of the spectrum include lymphomatoid papulosis and primary cutaneous anaplastic large cell lymphoma.
The liquid produced by squeezing or crushing fruit.
The meat of the domestic pig.
Contrast media that has a higher amplification and intensity than the surrounding tissue making the contrast look more opaque when seen in an x-ray.

label.value: Borderline Primary Cutaneous CD30-Positive T-Cell Lymphoproliferative Disorder

value.value: A CD30-positive T-cell lymphoproliferative disorder that arises from the skin and is characterized by overlapping morphological features between anaplastic large cell lymphoma and lymphomatoid papulosis.
Contrast media that has a lower amplification and intensity than the surrounding tissue making the contrast look less opaque when seen in an x-ray.
A variant of lymphomatoid papulosis characterized by the presence of scattered anaplastic large lymphocytes, often resembling Reed-Sternberg cells, admixed with acute and chronic inflammatory cells.
The sour to semi-sweet fruit of Citrus x paradisi. Grapefruit can have interactions with drugs, often increasing the effective potency of compounds.
